drastically influenced relations among the South Asian countries as well as their respective relations with their neighbours China, Myanmar, Iran, and Afghanistan. The recent nuclear deal between India and the US is also indicative of how energy and power politics are linked and how these new inter-linkages underlie relations between states. This book aims to give a South Asian perspective on the geopolitics of energy, with a central focus on India. The chapters address show India's global and regional foreign policy making has changed in light of India's search for energy and how this is affecting the relationship on a global level between India and the US, as well as on a regional level between India and the other Asian countries. The book also offers views from Pakistan and Bangladesh, as well as how this shifting reality is affecting relations between India and Southeast Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEnergy policyzIndiavCongresses. 0aEnergy policyzSouth AsiavCongresses. 0aEnergy policy--India--Congresses. 0aEnergy policy--South Asia--Congresses. 0aGeopoliticszSouth AsiavCongresses. 0aGeopolitics--South Asia--Congresses. 0aPower resourceszIndiavCongresses. 0aPower resourceszSouth AsiavCongresses. 0aPower resources--India--Congresses. 0aPower resources--South Asia--Congresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Energy.2bisacsh1 aFlorini, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHong, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIslam, M. Shahidul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKesavapany, K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLall, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLall, Marie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.